# Safety: forbidden shell commands

Cursor runs in this repo with auto-approve enabled in headless mode (`j work`
passes `--force --trust` to `cursor-agent`), so any tool call that would
otherwise pop an approval prompt now executes silently. To keep that safe, the
agent MUST refuse to execute the commands listed below and instead surface
them in chat for the user to confirm. This rule applies to BOTH headless and
interactive sessions — interactive cursor users still benefit from a hard
refuse-list for catastrophic commands.

## Forbidden commands — refuse and ask the user

Refuse to run, and ask the user before doing anything close to these:

- **Recursive force-deletes**: `rm -rf`, `rm -rf /`, `rm -rf ~`, `rm -rf .`,
  `rm -rf ..`, or any `rm -r{f,}` / `rm -fr` against `/`, `~`, `.`, `..`,
  `$HOME`, or any path outside the current task directory. This includes
  `find ... -delete`, `find ... -exec rm`, and other recursive-force delete
  idioms that escape the task scope.
- **Force-pushing protected branches**: `git push --force` /
  `git push --force-with-lease` / `git push -f` against `main`, `master`,
  `develop`, `release/*`, or any protected branch. Never force-push a branch
  you do not own.
- **History-rewriting on shared branches**: `git reset --hard` on a branch
  that has been pushed, `git clean -fdx`, `git clean -fdX`, `git rebase -i`,
  `git filter-branch`, `git filter-repo`, `git push --mirror`, or any
  history rewrite on a shared branch.
- **Privilege escalation**: `sudo` anything, `su -`, `doas`, `pkexec`, or
  any other root-elevation. The agent should never run as root.
- **Permission/ownership rewrites**: `chmod -R 777`, `chmod -R 000`,
  `chown -R` against paths outside the task scope, `setfacl -R`, or any
  recursive permission/owner change that touches `/`, `~`, `/etc`, `/var`,
  `/usr`, or system paths.
- **Raw device writes**: `dd if=... of=/dev/...`, `dd of=/dev/sd*`,
  `dd of=/dev/disk*`, `mkfs.*` (`mkfs.ext4`, `mkfs.xfs`, `mkfs.fat`, ...),
  `fdisk`, `parted`, `wipefs`, `shred` against block devices, or any raw
  write to `/dev/sd*`, `/dev/nvme*`, `/dev/disk*`, `/dev/mmcblk*`.
- **Fork bombs and resource-exhaustion gags**: `:(){ :|:& };:`, infinite
  background-spawn loops, `yes > /dev/sda`, etc.
- **Piping remote scripts straight into a shell**: `curl ... | sh`,
  `curl ... | bash`, `wget ... | sh`, `wget -qO- ... | bash`,
  `iwr ... | iex`, `Invoke-WebRequest ... | Invoke-Expression`, or any
  variant that downloads code and executes it without inspection.
- **Killing init / signalling PID 1**: `kill -9 1`, `kill -KILL 1`,
  `killall -9`, `killall -KILL`, `pkill -9 -1`, or any signal aimed at
  PID 1 / init / launchd / systemd.
- **Database destructives without a `WHERE`**: `DROP TABLE`, `DROP DATABASE`,
  `DROP SCHEMA`, `TRUNCATE`, `DELETE FROM <table>` without a `WHERE`
  clause, `UPDATE <table> SET ...` without a `WHERE` clause, or any
  schema/data-mutating SQL that is not narrowly scoped.
- **Cloud / IaC destructives**: `aws s3 rm --recursive`,
  `aws s3 rb --force`, `aws ec2 terminate-instances`,
  `aws rds delete-db-instance`, `gcloud ... delete`, `az ... delete`,
  `terraform destroy`, `terraform destroy -auto-approve`,
  `terraform apply -auto-approve` against production state,
  `kubectl delete ns <ns>`, `kubectl delete --all`,
  `kubectl drain --force --delete-emptydir-data`, `helm uninstall`
  against shared releases, or any other multi-resource cloud-side delete.
- **Package publishing**: `npm publish`, `yarn publish`, `pnpm publish`,
  `pip upload`, `twine upload`, `cargo publish`, `gem push`,
  `mvn deploy`, `gradle publish`, `dotnet nuget push`, `gh release create`,
  or any registry push. The agent must never publish on the user's behalf.
- **Mutating user-wide git config**: `git config --global ...`,
  `git config --system ...`, edits to `~/.gitconfig`, `/etc/gitconfig`,
  or `~/.config/git/config`. Repo-local `git config --local` is fine
  when scoped to this repository.
- **`eval` / `bash -c` on untrusted strings**: `eval "$..."` on data
  pulled from the network, the user's clipboard, or AI output;
  `bash -c "$..."`, `sh -c "$..."`, `zsh -c "$..."`, `python -c "$..."`,
  `node -e "$..."` etc. invoked on untrusted strings. If the agent
  generated the string itself it must paste the literal command for the
  user to read before executing.

## When in doubt

Stop. Print the proposed command verbatim in chat, explain what it would
do and which files / hosts / resources it would touch, and wait for the
user to confirm before executing. This applies to BOTH headless cursor
sessions (where `--force` would otherwise auto-approve every tool call)
and interactive sessions (where the user might fat-finger Enter on an
approval prompt). Refusing and asking is always the safe default; the
user can always re-run the command themselves if they really want it.
